00:00:57.902 --> 00:01:01.250 align:middle line:90%


00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:03.410 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm a general practitioner,
an emergency doctor,

00:01:03.410 --> 00:01:05.870 align:middle line:84%
and I set up something called
"The Doctor's Kitchen,"

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:08.990 align:middle line:84%
which is basically a YouTube
channel and social media

00:01:08.990 --> 00:01:13.970 align:middle line:84%
platforms where I teach
people the use of nutrition

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:16.730 align:middle line:84%
in medicine and how I'm trying
to inspire people that food is

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:17.600 align:middle line:90%
medicine.

00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:20.570 align:middle line:84%
And it's actually something I
started because of my patients,

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:22.955 align:middle line:84%
but my colleagues-- my
medical colleagues are all

00:01:22.955 --> 00:01:24.330 align:middle line:84%
interested in this
sort of thing.

00:01:24.330 --> 00:01:26.622 align:middle line:84%
We're now getting tons of
emails from medical students,

00:01:26.622 --> 00:01:28.760 align:middle line:84%
like, where'd you get
this knowledge from?

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:32.630 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, I just started
it on the back of that.

00:01:32.630 --> 00:01:35.075 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:35.075 --> 00:01:38.482 align:middle line:90%


00:01:38.482 --> 00:01:40.690 align:middle line:84%
There's been a couple of
catalysts throughout my life

00:01:40.690 --> 00:01:45.070 align:middle line:84%
that have sort of led
me to this sort of path.

00:01:45.070 --> 00:01:50.920 align:middle line:84%
The first one, I think, was
when my mom got ill herself.

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:56.050 align:middle line:84%
So she had anaphylaxis,
and from an unknown cause.

00:01:56.050 --> 00:01:57.730 align:middle line:84%
There wasn't really
a reason as to why

00:01:57.730 --> 00:01:59.490 align:middle line:84%
she kept on getting these
anaphylactic episodes.

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:01.240 align:middle line:84%
And if you don't know
what anaphylaxis is,

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:03.580 align:middle line:84%
it's basically where your
blood pressure goes down.

00:02:03.580 --> 00:02:05.470 align:middle line:84%
You have a severe
allergic reaction.

00:02:05.470 --> 00:02:07.500 align:middle line:84%
We usually have to treat
it with adrenaline.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:10.509 align:middle line:84%
She had every single
test you can think of.

00:02:10.509 --> 00:02:14.140 align:middle line:84%
Every single doctor, professor,
immunology, everything, and we

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:16.540 align:middle line:84%
couldn't really find
out what the reason was.

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:19.270 align:middle line:84%
So back then-- this is going
back, like, 15 years ago.

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:21.670 align:middle line:84%
She essentially put herself
on an elimination diet.

00:02:21.670 --> 00:02:25.180 align:middle line:84%
This is when I was in
early teens, like, 13, 14.

00:02:25.180 --> 00:02:26.540 align:middle line:90%
And she would only have greens.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:28.170 align:middle line:84%
She would only
have whole grains.

00:02:28.170 --> 00:02:29.170 align:middle line:90%
She wouldn't have dairy.

00:02:29.170 --> 00:02:31.810 align:middle line:84%
She wouldn't have meat,
nothing for about a year,

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:33.480 align:middle line:90%
and anaphylaxis just went.

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:35.650 align:middle line:84%
And that was always in
the back of my mind.

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:38.310 align:middle line:84%
We never really talked about it
when I was growing up too much,

00:02:38.310 --> 00:02:40.960 align:middle line:84%
not really the research she
put into it, or the emphasis

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:41.990 align:middle line:90%
or anything like that.

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:44.020 align:middle line:84%
But that was always in
the back of my head.

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:45.603 align:middle line:84%
When I went to med
school, I was like,

00:02:45.603 --> 00:02:48.593 align:middle line:84%
you can use food
in a medicinal way.

00:02:48.593 --> 00:02:51.010 align:middle line:84%
I don't really understand it,
and I didn't get the answers

00:02:51.010 --> 00:02:52.060 align:middle line:90%
to that throughout med school.

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:53.990 align:middle line:84%
But that was always at
the back of my head.

00:02:53.990 --> 00:02:56.140 align:middle line:84%
And then I actually
got ill myself as well.

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:59.380 align:middle line:84%
So I suffer something called
atrial fibrillation, so

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:00.850 align:middle line:90%
paroxysmal atrial fibrillation.

00:03:00.850 --> 00:03:03.070 align:middle line:84%
My heart rate goes to
180 beats per minute.

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:05.310 align:middle line:84%
Feel dizzy, get a little
bit of shortness of breath.

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:06.910 align:middle line:90%
Used to have it weekly.

00:03:06.910 --> 00:03:08.020 align:middle line:90%
There were some triggers.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:11.350 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes it could be a glass
wine, sometimes a heavy meal,

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:14.110 align:middle line:84%
sometimes a night shift in A&E.
I would just flip into this,

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:18.190 align:middle line:84%
and it would last, like, four
or five hours, or even 12 hours.

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:20.800 align:middle line:84%
And again, every single
test under the sun.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:22.492 align:middle line:84%
I had the
electrophysiology studies,

00:03:22.492 --> 00:03:23.950 align:middle line:84%
the wire that goes
into your groin,

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:26.710 align:middle line:84%
looks at your heart to see
if there's any aberrant

00:03:26.710 --> 00:03:28.960 align:middle line:84%
connections, aberrant
electrical impulses.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:30.040 align:middle line:90%
Couldn't find anything.

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:33.295 align:middle line:84%
So what the
discussion led to was

00:03:33.295 --> 00:03:35.170 align:middle line:84%
I should have an ablation,
which is basically

00:03:35.170 --> 00:03:37.780 align:middle line:84%
where you put a
wire into the heart

00:03:37.780 --> 00:03:41.200 align:middle line:84%
and you burn around an
area of the pulmonary vein

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:43.957 align:middle line:90%
where usually these cells fire.

00:03:43.957 --> 00:03:45.790 align:middle line:84%
And I thought about it,
and I had discussion

00:03:45.790 --> 00:03:47.170 align:middle line:90%
with a bunch of cardiologists.

00:03:47.170 --> 00:03:50.170 align:middle line:84%
And my mom, obviously, being the
naturopathic sort of influence

00:03:50.170 --> 00:03:53.080 align:middle line:84%
she is, she said, look, just
try things with your diet

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:55.310 align:middle line:90%
and just see what happens.

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:58.510 align:middle line:84%
So I basically tried a
whole bunch of things--

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:02.360 align:middle line:84%
detoxed completely, no caffeine,
no alcohol, clean diet,

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:03.160 align:middle line:90%
exercise.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:05.490 align:middle line:90%
Nothing worked, to be honest.

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:10.900 align:middle line:84%
But after about six months
of drinking spirulina

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:12.700 align:middle line:84%
and chlorella, and
really focusing

00:04:12.700 --> 00:04:15.430 align:middle line:84%
on a plant-based
whole diet, it sort of

00:04:15.430 --> 00:04:18.501 align:middle line:84%
went away for about
two or three years.

00:04:18.501 --> 00:04:19.959 align:middle line:84%
And I can count
the number of times

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:23.470 align:middle line:90%
I had AF on one hand in a year.

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:27.040 align:middle line:84%
going from once a week, there's
certainly been a correlation.

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:29.410 align:middle line:84%
And I can't really explain
that, and no medical person

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:31.880 align:middle line:84%
can explain it, no
cardiologist or anything.

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:34.660 align:middle line:84%
So it's quite it's
quite interesting how

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:36.040 align:middle line:84%
we have these sort
of experiences

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:38.770 align:middle line:90%
and it changes the trajectory.

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:40.960 align:middle line:84%
So those were the two main
catalysts, but then also

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:41.830 align:middle line:90%
patients.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:44.650 align:middle line:84%
So my patients who come
in to me in my GP office

00:04:44.650 --> 00:04:47.410 align:middle line:84%
and say, look, I've got IBS,
I've got autoimmune disease.

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:49.397 align:middle line:84%
Is anything in my diet
that can change that?

00:04:49.397 --> 00:04:50.980 align:middle line:84%
And the general
answer for a clinician

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:53.773 align:middle line:84%
is, there isn't evidence
to suggest anything.

00:04:53.773 --> 00:04:54.940 align:middle line:90%
So I have to do my research.

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:56.410 align:middle line:84%
I have to teach
myself nutrition.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:57.820 align:middle line:84%
I had to read all the
clinical journals.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:59.862 align:middle line:84%
I had to go to all the
global conferences looking

00:04:59.862 --> 00:05:02.290 align:middle line:84%
at the science behind
nutrition to make sure I'm not

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:03.652 align:middle line:90%
doing any harm as a clinician.

00:05:03.652 --> 00:05:05.360 align:middle line:84%
You know, I've taken
an oath, do no harm.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:06.885 align:middle line:84%
So anything that
I say is has got

00:05:06.885 --> 00:05:09.650 align:middle line:84%
to have an evidence
base behind it.

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:12.803 align:middle line:84%
And I used to just get
really late in my clinics,

00:05:12.803 --> 00:05:14.470 align:middle line:84%
talking to people
about recipes, talking

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:15.580 align:middle line:84%
to people about what
things they should

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:17.200 align:middle line:90%
be putting into their diet.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:19.522 align:middle line:84%
I'd always be the guy
people would go to

00:05:19.522 --> 00:05:20.980 align:middle line:84%
for nutrition
advice, so I thought,

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:22.900 align:middle line:90%
there's got to be an easier way.

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:25.150 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I started
"The Doctor's Kitchen," which

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:30.760 align:middle line:84%
is YouTube tutorials and
recipes and making it engaging.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:32.360 align:middle line:90%
I'm not an authoritative person.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:34.360 align:middle line:84%
I don't want it to be
like a prescriptive thing.

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:37.458 align:middle line:84%
I want you to be empowered
and inspired to look

00:05:37.458 --> 00:05:38.500 align:middle line:90%
for these foods yourself.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:40.032 align:middle line:84%
And when you go to
your supermarket,

00:05:40.032 --> 00:05:42.490 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at the greens,
you're looking at the colors.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:45.610 align:middle line:84%
You're realizing that
this is information.

00:05:45.610 --> 00:05:47.170 align:middle line:90%
This can impact your genes.

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:49.750 align:middle line:90%
This can impact your DNA makeup.

00:05:49.750 --> 00:05:53.590 align:middle line:84%
This can impact on your blood
sugar regulation and everything

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:56.200 align:middle line:84%
else, and to appreciate the
concept of bioindividuality

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:57.520 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:05:57.520 --> 00:05:59.730 align:middle line:84%
So it's been a bit
of a journey so far.

00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:02.195 align:middle line:84%
I'm very junior in
it, but it's exciting.

00:06:02.195 --> 00:06:02.995 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:02.995 --> 00:06:05.845 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:05.845 --> 00:06:08.700 align:middle line:90%


00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:12.300 align:middle line:84%
I haven't figured out why
nutrition doesn't play a bigger

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:14.580 align:middle line:90%
role in medical education.

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:16.500 align:middle line:84%
I went to one-- and
I'm not bragging here,

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:18.960 align:middle line:84%
but I went to one of the best
medical schools in the world.

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:22.410 align:middle line:84%
It's renowned for its
research capability,

00:06:22.410 --> 00:06:26.220 align:middle line:84%
and we only got, like, less
than 11 or 12 hours in nutrition

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:30.180 align:middle line:84%
in the whole of the six-year
course that I went to.

00:06:30.180 --> 00:06:32.220 align:middle line:84%
And it was kind
of a shock for me

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:35.250 align:middle line:84%
when I did my own research
after qualifying as a doctor,

00:06:35.250 --> 00:06:38.835 align:middle line:84%
after going to quite well
established medical university,

00:06:38.835 --> 00:06:40.710 align:middle line:84%
that there was all this
information out there

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:41.960 align:middle line:90%
that wasn't being given to us.

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:44.430 align:middle line:84%
And we were being taught the
same dogma, the same things

00:06:44.430 --> 00:06:45.960 align:middle line:84%
about saturated
fats, the same thing

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:49.230 align:middle line:84%
about having a largely
carbohydrate, starch-based diet

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:51.538 align:middle line:90%
for everyone.

00:06:51.538 --> 00:06:52.830 align:middle line:90%
It was a bit of a wake up call.

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:54.720 align:middle line:84%
I can't really
answer the question

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.670 align:middle line:84%
as to why we're not
using this information.

00:06:56.670 --> 00:06:59.700 align:middle line:84%
But what I can say
is that using myself

00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:02.910 align:middle line:84%
as a platform and
collective people

00:07:02.910 --> 00:07:05.120 align:middle line:84%
in the sort of wellness
sphere will bring it

00:07:05.120 --> 00:07:06.870 align:middle line:84%
more to the forefront,
and that's actually

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:10.430 align:middle line:84%
one of the things that I want to
bring into medical education--

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:13.140 align:middle line:84%
culinary medicine, teaching
medical students how to cook,

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:15.030 align:middle line:84%
teaching them the
beauty of food,

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:18.510 align:middle line:84%
and inspiring them that
disease prevention and disease

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:21.210 align:middle line:84%
treatment can be
hand-in-hand with nutrition.

00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:24.090 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:24.090 --> 00:07:27.460 align:middle line:90%


00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:32.190 align:middle line:84%
I was quite worried about
the backlash, if you like,

00:07:32.190 --> 00:07:34.920 align:middle line:84%
or the response from
my medical colleagues,

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:36.060 align:middle line:90%
not so much my patients.

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:38.340 align:middle line:84%
I think my patients would
have like really appreciated

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:40.680 align:middle line:84%
their doctor being
enthusiastic about food, trying

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:43.110 align:middle line:84%
to help them, because that's
essentially what we all do,

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:45.640 align:middle line:90%
that we're all trying to do.

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:48.180 align:middle line:84%
But the response my colleagues
has been really good so far.

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:50.730 align:middle line:84%
You've got a few people
are saying, how can you

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:53.710 align:middle line:84%
treat hay fever with matcha
teas or increasing your greens

00:07:53.710 --> 00:07:54.510 align:middle line:90%
and stuff.

00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:58.020 align:middle line:84%
If you use the evidence,
if I'm saying everything

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:02.065 align:middle line:84%
with an educated, unbiased
opinion, then people,

00:08:02.065 --> 00:08:02.940 align:middle line:90%
they pick up on that.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:03.780 align:middle line:90%
They understand it.

00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:06.420 align:middle line:84%
They understand where the
passion is coming from.

00:08:06.420 --> 00:08:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And there is a real
hunger these days.

00:08:08.310 --> 00:08:12.900 align:middle line:84%
There is a real interest from
the medical community in food

00:08:12.900 --> 00:08:15.188 align:middle line:84%
and medicine, and
I'm latching onto it

00:08:15.188 --> 00:08:16.980 align:middle line:84%
and I'm just putting
information out there.

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:18.240 align:middle line:90%
So it's been really encouraging.

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:19.573 align:middle line:90%
It's been a really good journey.

00:08:19.573 --> 00:08:21.840 align:middle line:84%
And I've met so many people
as well in this world

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:24.215 align:middle line:84%
like, obviously, yourself,
"Food Matters" and everything.

00:08:24.215 --> 00:08:27.330 align:middle line:84%
But across the world,
just being able to talk

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:31.310 align:middle line:84%
to people on the same
wavelength, share ideas.

00:08:31.310 --> 00:08:33.980 align:middle line:84%
The response for
a doctor cooking

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:36.120 align:middle line:84%
has been really interesting,
actually, really good

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:40.580 align:middle line:84%
because there's so much to
be said for talking about it,

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:42.330 align:middle line:84%
talking about putting
greens in your diet.

00:08:42.330 --> 00:08:45.480 align:middle line:84%
But if you show people that
you are doing yourself,

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:48.270 align:middle line:84%
you're more motivated
to tell them about it,

00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:50.700 align:middle line:84%
but they're more motivated to
say, my doctor's doing this.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:51.510 align:middle line:90%
My doctor is cooking.

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:52.380 align:middle line:90%
He's in the kitchen.

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:54.270 align:middle line:90%
It's got to be important.

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:57.040 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, that's sort of the
line I'm trying to take.

00:08:57.040 --> 00:08:59.920 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:03.280 align:middle line:90%


00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:05.000 align:middle line:90%
I think there's two ways.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.780 align:middle line:84%
One, the quality of the research
is always under scrutiny

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:09.430 align:middle line:84%
when it comes to
nutritional medicine.

00:09:09.430 --> 00:09:13.810 align:middle line:84%
It's really hard to use
certain qualities of research

00:09:13.810 --> 00:09:19.510 align:middle line:84%
to base cost-benefit analysis
on real generalizing changes

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:22.720 align:middle line:84%
to a big, bureaucratic,
monolithic organization

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:24.220 align:middle line:90%
like the NHS, for example.

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:27.550 align:middle line:84%
You've got to have some
real solid evidence.

00:09:27.550 --> 00:09:29.560 align:middle line:84%
It's a bit of a
contentious issue

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:31.260 align:middle line:84%
because even the
evidence that we've

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:33.280 align:middle line:84%
based a lot of our
nutritional guidelines on,

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:35.080 align:middle line:90%
you wouldn't bet your house on.

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:39.790 align:middle line:84%
But it's looking at the
quality of nutritional research

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:41.530 align:middle line:84%
that's coming up from
nutrition journals,

00:09:41.530 --> 00:09:43.930 align:middle line:90%
it isn't always there.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:45.940 align:middle line:84%
You've got RCTs, Randomized
Controlled Trials,

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.190 align:middle line:84%
which are, like, the base
of what everything looks at,

00:09:48.190 --> 00:09:51.100 align:middle line:84%
and meta analysis
and everything else.

00:09:51.100 --> 00:09:54.550 align:middle line:84%
What we look at a lot of
like food questionnaires,

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:56.440 align:middle line:84%
and there's a lot of
inherent bias with that.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:58.360 align:middle line:84%
So people are incline
knob to believe that.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:01.900 align:middle line:84%
The other thing-- and I think
this is the bigger factor--

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:05.140 align:middle line:84%
is that once you've been
taught a certain way

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:08.500 align:middle line:84%
from the medical establishment,
from peers that you hold

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:12.670 align:middle line:84%
in the highest regard, you're
going to defend your thinking

00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:15.570 align:middle line:84%
and the medical establishment
as much as possible.

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:17.020 align:middle line:84%
And I've been
victim to this well.

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:19.600 align:middle line:84%
When I found out about ketotic
diet for the first time

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:23.020 align:middle line:84%
or low carbohydrate, high
fat, my initial gut reaction

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:23.890 align:middle line:90%
is, that's wrong.

00:10:23.890 --> 00:10:24.730 align:middle line:90%
That's a fad.

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:25.980 align:middle line:90%
This is what I've been taught.

00:10:25.980 --> 00:10:27.850 align:middle line:84%
This is what my esteemed
professor taught me

00:10:27.850 --> 00:10:29.830 align:middle line:90%
in medical university.

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:31.920 align:middle line:84%
And you just defend
it automatically.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:34.710 align:middle line:84%
You automatically
antagonize anyone

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:39.130 align:middle line:84%
that questions your
own understanding.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:42.650 align:middle line:84%
And as a medical professional,
that's even heightened, I find.

00:10:42.650 --> 00:10:45.070 align:middle line:84%
But really, when you go
down to the nuts and bolts

00:10:45.070 --> 00:10:46.960 align:middle line:84%
and you look at the
evidence, and you

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:48.880 align:middle line:84%
listen to people-- as
a general practitioner,

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:50.830 align:middle line:90%
you're client facing.

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:53.710 align:middle line:84%
You're not just one of a huge
study of thousands of people.

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:54.940 align:middle line:90%
These are individuals.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:56.830 align:middle line:84%
You realize the impact
of bioindividuality.

00:10:56.830 --> 00:10:59.870 align:middle line:84%
You realize the impact of
one nutritional guideline

00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:00.962 align:middle line:90%
doesn't apply to everyone.

00:11:00.962 --> 00:11:02.920 align:middle line:84%
There's some people that
have a high propensity

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:04.120 align:middle line:90%
to insulin resistance.

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:06.010 align:middle line:84%
There's some people
that survived

00:11:06.010 --> 00:11:09.280 align:middle line:84%
culturally, ethnically, their
background, on a high-fat diet.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:11.050 align:middle line:84%
And this is what we
need to listen to.

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:15.310 align:middle line:84%
So it's a really
difficult one, but I

00:11:15.310 --> 00:11:17.500 align:middle line:84%
think going to the
future, we'll be able to--

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:21.470 align:middle line:84%
we'll learn to recognize
our patients as individuals.

00:11:21.470 --> 00:11:23.680 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
will pave the way

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:26.650 align:middle line:84%
for more nutritional guidance
and better nutrition guidance.

